  references:
    version: 2
    RefIds:
    - rid: 1264014519372087443
      type: {class: DialogueNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: You can create a choice node rather than a regular node from the inspector.
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
    - rid: 1264014519372087446
      type: {class: DialogueChoiceNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: This allows you to create responses to dialogue with different jump
          indices. These nodes do not use the jump index. Instead, They us a list
          of <b>Choice</b> objects to define string responses and jump indices.
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
        choices:
        - text: I don't get it, can you repeat?
          jumpIndex: 1
        - text: I see.
          jumpIndex: 2
    - rid: 1264014519372087447
      type: {class: DialogueNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: This is why regular nodes have a jump index. So that you can create
          "tree-like" dialogue around your choices.
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
    - rid: 1264014519372087448
      type: {class: DialogueChoiceNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: Try clicking on one of the choices here.
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
        choices:
        - text: 1
          jumpIndex: 4
        - text: 2
          jumpIndex: 5
    - rid: 1264014519372087449
      type: {class: DialogueNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: I choose option 1.
        characterToShow: 0
        jumpIndex: 6
    - rid: 1264014519372087450
      type: {class: DialogueNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: I choose option 2.
        characterToShow: 0
        jumpIndex: -1
    - rid: 1264014519372087451
      type: {class: DialogueNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: Note in this conversation object (find it in the inspector),  that
          regardless of which option you chose, this text node appeared next.
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
    - rid: 1264014519372087452
      type: {class: DialogueNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: 'ONE FINAL IMPORTANT DETAIL: setting the jump index to beyond the last
          index (so that INCLUDES trying to set it to the Length of the list)  will
          end the dialogue immediately.'
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
    - rid: 1264014519372087462
      type: {class: DialogueChoiceNode, ns: Dialogue, asm: Assembly-CSharp}
      data:
        text: See how this last choice node will try to jump beyond the end of the
          list, immediately ending the conversation.
        characterToShow: 2
        jumpIndex: -1
        choices:
        - text: End the Dialogue
          jumpIndex: 9
        - text: Start Over
          jumpIndex: 0
